"    </a>",
"    <div id=\"topicText\">",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2283886\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What is a diaper rash?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;A diaper rash is a skin rash that happens anywhere in the area that is covered by a diaper. Diaper rashes are very common. They can occur in any baby or child who wears a diaper.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Most diaper rashes can be treated at home and go away after a few days.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2283893\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What causes diaper rash?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Diaper rash can be caused by:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bullet-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        The urine or bowel movement in the diaper &mdash; These can irritate the skin. Diaper rashes are especially common after a baby has diarrhea or has taken antibiotic medicines.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Perfumes or dyes in a diaper that a baby&rsquo;s skin is allergic to",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Skin conditions or infections that happen in the diaper area but are not caused by wearing a diaper",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2283900\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What are the symptoms of a diaper rash?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Symptoms depend on the cause of the rash. They can include:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bulletCompact-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Red, painful, or itchy skin",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Raised, peeling, or scaly areas",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Yellow blisters filled with fluid",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      If a baby&rsquo;s diaper rash is caused by a skin condition or infection, the rash can be on other body parts, too.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2283907\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       Should I see a doctor or nurse?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Most people can treat the rash at home and do not need to see a doctor or nurse. But you should see a doctor or nurse if:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bulletCompact-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        The rash gets worse or doesn&rsquo;t get better after a few days of treatment",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Your baby has diarrhea or a fever of 100.4&deg;F (38&deg;C) or more",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2283914\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       How should I treat the diaper rash?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;To treat your baby&rsquo;s diaper rash, you should:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bullet-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Take the diaper off to air out the skin as much as possible",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Check your baby&rsquo;s diaper every 2 or 3 hours, and change it when it is wet",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Change your baby&rsquo;s diaper right after each bowel movement",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Gently clean the area covered by the diaper &mdash; Use warm water and a soft cloth. If you use soap, use one that is mild and unscented. If the skin is peeling or sore, you can use a plastic squeeze bottle filled with warm water. Pat the area dry with a soft towel afterward.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Put a skin ointment or paste on the area each time you change the diaper &mdash; Use a product that has",
"        <a class=\"drug drug_patient\" href=\"mobipreview.htm?14/25/14740?source=see_link\">",
"         zinc oxide",
"        </a>",
"        or petrolatum in it.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Use disposable diapers instead of cloth diapers (when your baby has a diaper rash)",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      If the rash is severe or infected, your doctor might prescribe a medicine for you to use on the area.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2283921\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       How can diaper rashes be prevented?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;To help prevent your baby from getting a diaper rash, you can:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bullet-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Change your baby&rsquo;s diaper often",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Clean the diaper area gently &mdash; Use warm water and a soft cloth. If you use soap, use one that is mild and unscented. Pat the area dry with a soft towel afterward.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Use unscented baby wipes without alcohol (if you use baby wipes)",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Use a diaper ointment or paste on the area each time you change the diaper",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
